    <div style=" font-size: 11px;">
        <p>
            <strong>FAQs
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>
                We have a license to use this image, why are you contacting me?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Great! If you hold a valid license, please get in touch as soon as possible with
            a copy so we can update our records accordingly. We do apologize
            for any confusion and inconvenience if you hold a license for
            this use.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>I've removed the image, why do I still have to pay? 
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            We appreciate your efforts to remedy the infringement, however, our client did not
            receive any payment for the use which already occurred. We hope
            you can appreciate the philosophy that photographers and other
            visual artists deserve to earn a living wage and fair compensation
            for use of their work.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>What is a retroactive license?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            A retroactive license simply gives you permission to use the image in the past.
        </p>
        <p>
            If you would like to license the image for future use, please let us know so we can
            recalculate a price for you.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>
                There was no watermark on the image, how do I know it's copyrighted?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Copyright subsists upon the moment of a works creation (eg. when the shutter closes
            on the camera) and lasts the author's life plus seventy years.
            It is not reliant on a watermark or any other copyright management
            information. Not knowing who the copyright holder is to an image,
            does not give you the right to use it without the creator's permission.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>
                Our web designer/contractor uploaded this photo, why are we
                responsible?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            It is your responsibility to ensure that web designers, other contractors, and employees
            understand and abide by copyright law. As the one ultimately
            benefitting from the use of the work, you are the one responsible
            for paying the license fees. We encourage you to reach out to
            your web designer or other contractor and work out a solution
            separately. Some forms of business insurance may be able to cover
            this.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>I found this image on Google, doesn't that make it free?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Images found on search engines are still subject to copyright. Search engines and
            the like, are not free image websites and permission must always
            be sought from the copyright holder. This is why Google displays
            clearly in their image search “Images may be subject to copyright”
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Can I contact the artist directly?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            LAPIXA has been engaged exclusively to pursue this case of copyright infringement.
            All communications regarding this matter must be directed to
            LAPIXA or its appointed attorney.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>I provided credit to the artist, isn't that enough? 
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            While it's great to credit the work's creator, permission still needs to be sought
            before using an image.
        </p>
        <p>
            For many of our clients, this is how they make a living and attribution alone is
            not sufficient.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>
                This image is under a creative commons license, why do I have to pay to
                use it?
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            The creative commons license is only valid if the terms are adhered to. If you have
            received a letter from LAPIXA, or one of our lawyers, this means
            we have found the terms of the license have been breached and
            therefore the license is automatically and immediately terminated.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>How do I avoid copyright infringement in future? 
            </strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            The general rule of thumb here is to ensure that licenses are held for all content
            posted on your website. Always contact the copyright holder,
            or its agent, for permission to use the image before publishing
            it.
        </p>
